[src:fast-exponentiation/euler-s-totient-function] The special case where n is prime is known as Fermat's little theorem.
[src:fast-exponentiation/euler-s-totient-function] This follows from Lagrange's theorem and the fact that *φ*(*n*) is the order of the multiplicative group of integers modulo n.
[src:fast-exponentiation/euler-s-totient-function] The RSA cryptosystem is based on this theorem: it implies that the inverse of the function *a* ↦ *ae* mod *n*, where e is the (public) encryption exponent, is the function *b* ↦ *bd* mod *n*, where d, the (private) decryption exponent, is the multiplicative inverse of e modulo *φ*(*n*).
[src:fast-exponentiation/euler-s-totient-function] The difficulty of computing *φ*(*n*) without knowing the factorization of n is thus the difficulty of computing d: this is known as the RSA problem which can be solved by factoring n.
[src:fast-exponentiation/euler-s-totient-function] The owner of the private key knows the factorization, since an RSA private key is constructed by choosing n as the product of two (randomly chosen) large primes p and q.
[src:fast-exponentiation/euler-s-totient-function] Only n is publicly disclosed, and given the difficulty to factor large numbers we have the guarantee that no one else knows the factorization.
